{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / Problem\n\nThe `rebar-implement` skill (`examples/agent-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md`) dispatches an\nimplementation subagent in Phase 4d but never specifies a model tier. In both Claude Code and\nCodex CLI an unset model inherits the orchestrator's (expensive) model, so the subagent silently\nruns on the strongest tier — the anti-pattern that erases any token saving. The skill also lacks\nguidance on which work is safe to delegate to a cheaper model and how to escalate when a cheap\nimplementer is insufficient.\n\n## Approach\n\nAdd a `## Model tiering` operating principle and targeted amendments to Phases 3, 4a, 4d, plus a\nnew `### 4e-bis` escalation ladder. Frame tiers as *capabilities* (strong / standard / cheap)\nwith Claude Code and Codex CLI example mappings, rather than hardcoding product names — the skill\nis cross-harness (`AGENTS.md`-class prose read by non-Claude harnesses) and model names drift\nacross releases. The held-out-TDD invariant is preserved: test-authoring (4b) and held-out\nvalidation (4e, already in the file) stay strong-tier, and a *separate* implementer always\nexists, so a green result still means the implementer could not tailor code to the full oracle.\nThe design was pressure-tested across five adversarial review rounds before this change.\n\nRejected alternative: naming Opus/Sonnet/Haiku directly — simpler but breaks portability to\nCodex and rots as models are renamed.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `examples/agent-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md` — the only file changed; prose-only\n  (~+111/-2 lines). No source code, no behavior, no tests.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A `## Model tiering` section exists with a capability-tier table naming both a Claude Code\n      and a Codex CLI example per tier — checked by `grep -n 'Model tiering' && grep -c '^| '`.\n- [ ] Phase 4d states a standard-tier default, a cheap-tier-only-for-transcription rule, and a\n      constraints-in-brief requirement — checked by reading section 4d.\n- [ ] A `### 4e-bis` escalation ladder exists that distinguishes normal held-out iteration\n      (no escalation) from the model-weakness escalation triggers — checked by reading it.\n- [ ] No hardcoded module-size number is introduced; the brief cites\n      `.github/module-size-limit.txt` (which contains `800`) as the source of truth — checked by\n      grep for the filename in SKILL.md.\n- [ ] Phase 3 dispatch-by-kind includes a seam note directing research/discovery/grep-shaped\n      non-code leaves to the cheap/fast tier — checked by grep for \"tier\" within the Phase 3\n      non-code-leaf bullet.\n- [ ] Phase 4a carries an explicit annotation that the existing-coverage search is cheap-shaped\n      but spec derivation stays strong-tier by choice — checked by reading Phase 4a.\n- [ ] Change is docs-only and `make lint` passes — checked by `git diff --stat` showing only the\n      SKILL.md path and a clean lint run.\n\nNo `## Testing` section: this is a prose/docs change with no new testable behavior. \"Transcription\"\nin AC2 means a leaf whose happy-path test fully pins the code (1–2 files), so implementing it is\nmechanical transcription rather than design."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784744651419359001,"uuid":"c286dff6-1088-46dc-b7fd-3b651f0fbac2"}